import Layout from '../../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import AdminHelpDoc from '../../../components/AdminHelpDoc.astro';
---

<Layout title="Camp May 9 — Evening Session Outline | Admin" noindex={true}>
  <AdminHelpDoc title="Camp May 9 — Evening Recruiting Session" tag="Camp prep">
    <p><strong>Date:</strong> Saturday May 9, 2026 · <strong>Time:</strong> ~6:30-8:00pm (after 2-5pm field session + dinner break) · <strong>Audience:</strong> Players + parents in same room (deliberate) · <strong>Length:</strong> 75-90 min</p>
    <p><strong>Goal:</strong> Reset recruiting cadence. Every player leaves with a school list, a content plan, and a coach-outreach commitment for the next 4 weeks.</p>

    <hr />

    <h2>Pre-Session Setup</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Print player one-pagers (their <code>players.json</code> data + GPA + measurables) — 1 per family</li>
      <li>Bring laptop + projector (or large monitor)</li>
      <li>Pull program-match <code>/admin/outreach</code> open in browser — show the live CRM (heat scores, threads, sends)</li>
      <li>Pull <code>/recruiting</code> page open — show the public coach hub</li>
      <li>Bring printed copy of webinar takeaways doc for any parent who asks for receipts</li>
      <li>Confirm everyone got the parent email + replied with their 5 answers (chase missing replies day-of)</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Session Flow</h2>

    <h3>[0:00 — 0:05] Welcome + frame</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Thank them. Acknowledge the long day on the field.</li>
      <li>Frame: <em>"This is the most important meeting we'll have this season. Not a pep talk. We're going to do work."</em></li>
      <li>Phones away. Players + parents sitting together.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>[0:05 — 0:20] What coaches are actually evaluating</h3>
    <p><strong>Anchor concept: Be the butter.</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Tell the ingredient-list story (Adam Glickman, Firecrackers): coaches show up with a shopping list. They are not browsing. Spring is when you get on the list.</li>
      <li>Tell the .300 hitter story: a great hitter fails 7/10 times. They recruit how you handle the failure.</li>
      <li>The Lexi / Jackie Joseph story (Donny's): kid went 0-for-3 with a strikeout, got the offer. Coach saw fearless swing after the K. The thing she thought was a bad showcase was actually her best at-bat.</li>
      <li>Drive home: <strong>once a coach is at your game, athleticism is settled. They're now watching character.</strong> Body language. Hustle. Eye contact. Dugout behavior. Who carries the gear.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>[0:20 — 0:30] The disagreement — and what we do differently</h3>
    <p><strong>Anchor concept: We drive the bus <em>with</em> you, not for you.</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Most travel programs say "you drive, we just play tournaments." We don't.</li>
      <li><strong>You drive on:</strong> effort, character, communication, sending emails, doing the homework, going to camps.</li>
      <li><strong>We drive on:</strong> advocacy, school list curation, coach relationships, tracking, follow-up updates.</li>
      <li>Show the live program-match outreach CRM (heat scores, last pixel hit, send/reply log). Show a player profile page with the pixel firing — and explain that the pixel feeds program-match automatically.</li>
      <li>The catch: <strong>"If you're not in, I'm not in. We will match your effort. We will not replace it."</strong></li>
    </ul>

    <h3>[0:30 — 0:45] The honest evaluation talk</h3>
    <p><strong>Anchor concept: Cast a wide net. D1-or-bust is dead.</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li>1300+ college softball programs. Most families know the top 25.</li>
      <li>Tell Tori's story: "What's your top school?" — "Texas A&M." — "Why?" — "They were the first school to look at me." That's not a why.</li>
      <li>The "potential" trap: potential means you haven't done it yet. Don't get drunk on rankings.</li>
      <li>We will be honest with you. If we tell a coach you're coachable, you are. That's how we keep the door open with coaches over time.</li>
      <li>Wide net = D1, D2, D3, NAIA, JUCO, in that order of <em>fit</em>, not prestige.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>[0:45 — 1:00] NIL / rev-share / portal — what's real, what's noise</h3>
    <p><strong>Quick. Don't dwell. Goal: deflate the noise so kids stop chasing rumored money.</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Post-House settlement, ~100 schools have meaningful money. ~98% of softball recruits, NIL is not a recruiting decision factor.</li>
      <li>80-90% of rev-share goes to football and basketball. Crumbs left for softball.</li>
      <li>Personal-brand NIL exists for kids with social media reach — that's effort outside the sport.</li>
      <li>Transfer portal has tightened roster spots. Means our digital footprint matters more, not less.</li>
      <li><strong>Don't pick a school chasing rumored money. Pick the fit.</strong></li>
    </ul>

    <h3>[1:00 — 1:25] Per-player working session</h3>
    <p><strong>This is the meat of the meeting.</strong></p>
    <p>Pull each player + parent up one at a time (or break into stations if too many — 4-5 min each):</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Review their reply to the parent email (top 10 schools, last camp, last video, coaches emailed)</li>
      <li>Mark which schools are realistic / stretch / need to discover</li>
      <li>Assign <strong>one concrete homework item</strong> for each player before next tournament</li>
      <li>Add 3-5 of their target coaches to the CRM <strong>live, in front of them</strong> — show them this is real</li>
    </ul>
    <p>If 14 players × 4 min = 56 min — too long. Either:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>(a) Run 3 stations in parallel (Mike + 2 assistant coaches)</li>
      <li>(b) Do top 5 priority players publicly, rest in 1:1 follow-ups within 7 days</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Decide which by May 7.</strong> Default: stations.</p>

    <h3>[1:25 — 1:30] Close + commitments</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Each player states out loud: <strong>one thing she'll do this week.</strong> (Send 3 emails. Post a video. Research 5 schools. Sign up for a camp.)</li>
      <li>Each parent states: <strong>one thing they will stop doing or start doing.</strong> (Examples: "stop coaching from the bleachers." "Start letting her email coaches herself.")</li>
      <li>Calendar: next tournament is <strong>Show Me The Money, Newberry FL, June 5-8</strong> — we have ~4 weeks. We will check in by email at week 2 and week 4.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Post-Session</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Send recap email Sunday May 10 with each player's homework + the team-wide commitments list</li>
      <li>Update each uncommitted player's CRM with the schools we agreed on</li>
      <li>Schedule 1:1 follow-up calls for any player who didn't get a station slot</li>
      <li>Update internal docs if we learn anything from the Q&A worth adding</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Failure modes to watch for</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>A parent gets defensive about body-language critique.</strong> Stay calm. Reframe: <em>"I'm not saying you're doing it wrong. I'm telling you what college coaches told us they look for. Decide what to do with that."</em></li>
      <li><strong>A player doesn't have a school list.</strong> Don't shame. Use the time to build one in the room — Stars priority is to widen the view, not test her preparation.</li>
      <li><strong>A parent challenges the "drive the bus" framing — wants more from Stars.</strong> Lean in. <em>"Tell me what you need. If it's reasonable, we'll add it. If it's not, I'll be honest about why."</em></li>
      <li><strong>The room runs long.</strong> Cut the NIL section first — it's deflation, not action. The 1:1 stations are the irreplaceable part.</li>
    </ul>
  </AdminHelpDoc>
</Layout>
